"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125603","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-14","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education publishes data on prison education participation and completion rates and details on the academic years 2010/11 to 2017/18 can be found at the following link: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/761349/201718_Nov_MAIN_OLASS_Particpation_FINALv1.xlsx" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/761349/201718_Nov_MAIN_OLASS_Particpation_FINALv1.xlsx</a></p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2019-05-14T16:00:56.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125603/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125603/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-05-09","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the educational courses on offer to offenders at each prison (a) before and (b) after 1 April 2019.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","252595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125604","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-14","<p>It is for the new education providers to determine how many staff they need to deliver the requirements of the contracts let under the Prison Education Framework and the Dynamic Purchasing System.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2019-05-14T16:03:49.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125604/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125604/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-05-09","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many education staff have been placed at risk of redundancy at each prison since the introduction of new commissioning arrangements on 1 April 2019.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","252596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125605","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-14","<p>The new prison education commissioning arrangements are at a very early stage. It is not possible to provide an assessment of progress at this point.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2019-05-14T15:58:18.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125605/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125605/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-05-09","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of new prison education commissioning arrangements on the effectiveness of Through The Gate services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","252597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125606","Department for Education","false","2019-05-16","<p>Widening access and participation in higher education is a priority for the government. This means that everyone with the capability to succeed in higher education should have the opportunity to participate, regardless of their background or where they grew up.</p><p>We have made real progress in ensuring universities are open to all, with record rates of disadvantaged 18-year-olds in higher education. However, we know there is further to go to maximise the potential of the talent out there, so it is vital that we build on this progress.</p><p>Higher education providers need to use good quality and meaningful data to identify disadvantage in order to effectively address disparities in access and participation in higher education. We encourage institutions to use a range of measures to identify disadvantage, including individual-level indicators, area data (such as Participation of Local Areas, Index of Multiple Deprivation or postcode classification from ACORN), school data, intersectional data such as Universities and Colleges Admissions Service’s (UCAS) Multiple Equality Measure, and participation in outreach activities. To this end, we are working with the Office for Students (OfS), UCAS and sector representatives to further explore how we can support universities to improve and enhance access to data.</p><p>We want institutions to consider a broad range of information in their offers, including the context in which a student’s results were achieved. We are committed to helping universities progress in their efforts to improve access and successful participation for under-represented groups.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","252599","2019-05-16T15:31:24.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125606/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125606/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-05-09","Universities: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions he has had with representatives of universities on the sharing of applicants’ pupil premium status and ethnicity directly with universities in order to enabling progress on access and participation.","false","Biography information for Ben Bradley","Mansfield","Ben Bradley","252598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125607","Department for Education","false","2019-05-16","<p>Widening access and participation in higher education is a priority for the government. This means that everyone with the capability to succeed in higher education should have the opportunity to participate, regardless of their background or where they grew up.</p><p>We have made real progress in ensuring universities are open to all, with record rates of disadvantaged 18-year-olds in higher education. However, we know there is further to go to maximise the potential of the talent out there, so it is vital that we build on this progress.</p><p>Higher education providers need to use good quality and meaningful data to identify disadvantage in order to effectively address disparities in access and participation in higher education. We encourage institutions to use a range of measures to identify disadvantage, including individual-level indicators, area data (such as Participation of Local Areas, Index of Multiple Deprivation or postcode classification from ACORN), school data, intersectional data such as Universities and Colleges Admissions Service’s (UCAS) Multiple Equality Measure, and participation in outreach activities. To this end, we are working with the Office for Students (OfS), UCAS and sector representatives to further explore how we can support universities to improve and enhance access to data.</p><p>We want institutions to consider a broad range of information in their offers, including the context in which a student’s results were achieved. We are committed to helping universities progress in their efforts to improve access and successful participation for under-represented groups.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","252598","2019-05-16T15:31:24.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125607/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125607/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-05-09","Universities: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions he has had with the Office for Students on the transmission of data on applicants’ pupil premium status and ethnicity directly to universities in order to support universities’ work on widening participation and access.","false","Biography information for Ben Bradley","Mansfield","Ben Bradley","252599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125608","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-17","<p>The Government’s preferred outcome remains that the UK should leave the EU in an orderly fashion with a Withdrawal Agreement. In this circumstance, the EU Regulations that cover freight connectivity (in particular the road measure, but also addressed by the aviation regulation in the context of air freight) would not need to come into effect. However, if the UK does leave the EU without having concluded a Withdrawal Agreement then the measure guarantees rights for UK carriers to carry goods to and from the EU until the end of December, which provides welcome certainty for UK carriers and their customers.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2019-05-17T09:32:56.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125608/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125608/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-09","Freight: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the merits of the freight connectivity proposals ratified by the European Union for enforcement in a situation where no withdrawal agreement is reached.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","252499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125609","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-17","<p>According to the Daily Air Quality Index, there were ‘moderate’ to ‘very high’ levels of air pollution in some areas of the UK between 7 and 8 April 2019 and between 15 and 25 April 2019. The figures for emergency ambulance dispatches relating to coronary heart disease in this period are not available in the format requested and a comparative assessment has not been made.</p><p>In January 2019, the Government launched the Clean Air Strategy, which sets out plans for dealing with all sources of air pollution to save lives, protect nature and boost the economy.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-17T12:30:27.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125609/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125609/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-09","Heart Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what comparative estimate he has made of the number of emergency ambulance dispatches for coronary heart disease in affected areas in England during the pollution episode in April 2019 and (a) the expected average and (b) the average over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","252463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125610","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-16","<p>During air pollution episodes, Defra works closely with Public Health England and a network of health charities to ensure that key health messages are communicated to those who are vulnerable to the effects of air pollution, in addition to communicating through our normal digital channels.</p><p> </p><p>We recommend people visit <a href="http://uk-air.defra.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://uk-air.defra.gov.uk/</a> for the latest forecasts and health advice or check our Twitter feed @DefraUKAir.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-05-16T12:06:23.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125610/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125610/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-09","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what channels of communication his Department uses to alert the general public to a pollution episode.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","252464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125611","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-16","<p>The Government strongly condemns discrimination against minorities, including through seizure of land from minority groups. We are deeply concerned about persecution of religious minorities and restrictions on the freedom of religion or belief in Pakistan.</p><p>The Prime Minister emphasised the importance of advancing the rights of minorities during her telephone call with Imran Khan in August 2018 following his election as Prime Minister of Pakistan. The Minister of State for the Commonwealth and the UN, Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon raised our concerns about Freedom of Religion or Belief and the protection of minority religious communities with Pakistan's Human Rights Minister during his visit to Pakistan in February 2019.</p><p>At the UN Universal Periodic Review of Pakistan in November 2017, the UK pressed Pakistan to strengthen the protection of minorities, including by establishing an independent National Commission for Minorities.</p><p>We recognise the drive by Prime Minister Imran Khan to stop land seizures. We regularly raise our concerns about the protection of minority communities with the Government of Pakistan at senior levels. We will continue to urge the Government of Pakistan to guarantee fully the rights of all Pakistani citizens, including religious minorities, and to honour its international obligations.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-05-16T09:01:21.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125611/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125611/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-05-09","Pakistan: Minority Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has discussed with his Pakistani counterpart land grabbing from members of religious minorities in that country.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","252500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125612","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-15","<p>We continue to be concerned about restrictions on the construction of places of worship in Egypt. All religious minorities ought to be able practise their faith without constraints or discrimination. The 2016 Church Building Law represents a step forward in this area, increasing the number of registered churches in Egypt.</p><p>We welcome other positive developments concerning religious freedom, including President Sisi's calls for peaceful coexistence and the Government of Egypt's expression of support for the rights of Christians and for religious tolerance. The Prime Minister's Special Envoy for Freedom of Religion or Belief, Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon, reaffirmed our mutual commitment to freedom of religion or belief during his visit to Cairo in November.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-05-15T14:26:30.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125612/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125612/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-05-09","Egypt: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Egyptian counterpart on the effect of laws restricting the construction of churches on religious freedom.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","252501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125613","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-16","<p>The data is not available in the precise format requested.</p><p>Based on the latest Assuring Transformation (AT) data for March 2019, we estimate that around 30% of planned transfers under the Transforming Care programme would be to another inpatient facility.</p><p>The most recent AT data indicates that in March 2019, 25 people were transferred to another hospital setting. This was 16% of the total number of people discharged or transferred within the month.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2019, there were 105 delayed discharges recorded in the AT data. The reason for the delayed discharge was recorded as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Reason for delayed discharge</p></td><td><p>Number of inpatients</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of agreed health care funding</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of agreed social care funding</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting non-acute National Health Service care</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting residential home</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting nursing home</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting care package in own home</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting community equipment</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Patient or family choice</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of local health provision</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of social care support</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of suitable housing provision</p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other reason for delay</p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The reasons do not sum to the total number of delays as multiple reasons may be assigned to an individual patient.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2019, 965 patients have a discharge planned to a community or residential setting.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","252528 ; 252529 ; 252530","2019-05-16T11:33:29.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125613/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125613/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-09","Hospitals: Discharges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of planned transfers under the Transforming Care programme specify that the person will move into another in-patient facility.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","252527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125614","Home Office","false","2019-05-17","<p>The Government recognises the damaging impact that violence and abuse can have, not only for victims, but also for businesses, and the wider community. We continue to work closely with retailers, the police and others to tackle these crimes.</p><p>Some information is available on the number of assaults and threats made against staff in the Wholesale and retail sector working in premises in England and Wales from the Home Office Commercial Victimisation. Annual estimates are available for each year since 2012 and are published in the ‘Crime against businesses’ tables which can be found here:<br><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/703372/crime-against-businesses-comparison-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/703372/crime-against-businesses-comparison-2017-tables.ods</a></p><p>On 5 April, the Government launched a Call for Evidence on violence and abuse toward shop staff, to further understand the scale of the issue and in-form our response.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-05-17T08:58:26.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125614/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125614/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-05-09","Retail Trade: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many violent attacks on staff working in retail premises there were in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","252502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125615","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-16","<p>The data is not available in the precise format requested.</p><p>Based on the latest Assuring Transformation (AT) data for March 2019, we estimate that around 30% of planned transfers under the Transforming Care programme would be to another inpatient facility.</p><p>The most recent AT data indicates that in March 2019, 25 people were transferred to another hospital setting. This was 16% of the total number of people discharged or transferred within the month.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2019, there were 105 delayed discharges recorded in the AT data. The reason for the delayed discharge was recorded as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Reason for delayed discharge</p></td><td><p>Number of inpatients</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of agreed health care funding</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of agreed social care funding</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting non-acute National Health Service care</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting residential home</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting nursing home</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting care package in own home</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting community equipment</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Patient or family choice</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of local health provision</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of social care support</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lack of suitable housing provision</p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other reason for delay</p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The reasons do not sum to the total number of delays as multiple reasons may be assigned to an individual patient.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2019, 965 patients have a discharge planned to a community or residential setting.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> <