"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125689","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-14","<p>The Department does not collect information relating to rural proofing reviews.</p><p>In <em>Strengthened Local Enterprise Partnerships, </em>Government set out its expectation that all LEPs should seek to be representative of their local economies and ensure that through their development of economic strategy for their areas, LEPs prioritise action needed to boost productivity, earning power and competitiveness across their local economies, rural as well as urban.</p><p>In line with the Industrial Strategy, we have set Local Enterprise Partnerships a single mission to deliver Local Industrial Strategies to promote productivity. This should include a focus on the foundations of productivity and identify priorities across Ideas, People, Infrastructure, Business Environment and Places.</p><p>For many LEP areas this will involve identifying weaknesses in productivity across their local areas, such as in isolated rural or urban communities, promoting inclusive growth by using existing national and local funding.</p><p> </p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-05-14T12:32:50.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125689/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125689/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-09","Local Enterprise Partnerships: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and which Local Enterprise Partnerships have undertaken a rural proofing review for policies adopted during 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","252507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125690","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-05-15","<p>The Office for Product Safety and Standards has conducted a full review into Whirlpool’s modification programme for tumble dryers. This review concluded that the risk to modified tumble dryers was low. A decision letter was sent to Whirlpool, placing a number of requirements on the company.</p><p> </p><p>The Chief Executive of the Office for Product Safety and Standards met senior Whirlpool officials 2nd May to advise them of concerns regarding the adequacy of their response to the requirements placed upon them and advised them on steps necessary to fulfil their obligations.</p><p> </p><p>OPSS is closely monitoring the response of Whirlpool and further steps will be taken if the response is not satisfactory. Consumer safety is a key priority and the Government will hold the company to account.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-05-15T13:42:23.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125690/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125690/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-05-09","Whirlpool Corporation: Tumble Dryers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of whether Whirlpool has (a) implemented adequate product safety checks and (b) carried out satisfactory repairs on models of tumble dryer that had been found faulty.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","252626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125691","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-05-14","<p>We published the revised National Planning Policy Framework in 2018, setting out national planning policies for supporting high quality communications in England. These include that the planning policies and decisions of local planning authorities should support the expansion of electronic communications networks, such as 5G.</p><p>We have also introduced a range of permitted development rights to support the delivery of mobile infrastructure, including legislating for higher masts in 2016, whilst also protecting local amenity.</p><p>We hope that these measures will be used by industry, alongside proactive engagement with the planning system, to ensure delivery of 5G. However, we will keep planning regulations under review.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-05-14T17:01:03.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125691/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125691/answer","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125691/answer/previousversion/117983","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-05-09","5G","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of of current permitted development rights for (a) mobile infrastructure and (b) 5G in helping the UK become a world-leading 5G economy.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","252479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125692","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-16","<p>Article 130 of the Withdrawal Agreement provides for the relative stability keys for the allocation of fishing opportunities to be maintained during the implementation period. This provision is intended to ensure that the UK’s share of quota cannot be reduced and that the UK will continue to be able to invoke Hague Preference during the implementation period. The recitals to the basic Common Fisheries Policy Regulation (Regulation 1380/2013) make clear that relative stability should take account of the Hague Resolution and therefore this would be included in the reference to ‘relative stability keys’ in Article 130.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-05-16T14:23:31.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125692/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125692/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-09","Fisheries: Quotas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the reference to article 43(3) of the TFEU and the relative stability keys referred to in Article 130 of the Withdrawal Agreement include the interpretive recitals 36 and 37 concerning Hague Preference which are contained within EU regulation 1380/2013.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","252565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125693","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-17","<p>The number of individuals proceeded against and convicted of an assault against an emergency worker can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/802035/outcomes-by-offence-tool-2018.xlsx" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/802035/outcomes-by-offence-tool-2018.xlsx</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Filter by ‘Offence’ for:</p><p> </p><p>`8.22 Assault against an emergency worker’.</p><p> </p><p>This link also provides information on the average length of sentence (in months) given to those convicted of this offence.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to obtain an estimate of the number of people who have received an increased sentence for an offence specified as aggravated under the Assaults on Emergency Workers (Offences) Act 2018. Detailed information may be held on individual court records but to be able to identify these cases we would have to access these individual court records which would be of disproportionate cost.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","252562 ; 252563 ; 252564","2019-05-17T13:25:53.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125693/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125693/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-05-09","Emergency Services: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have received an increased sentence for an offence specified as aggravated under the Assaults on Emergency Workers (Offences) Act 2018.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","252566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125694","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-16","<p>The work of most staff in Defra and its arms’ length bodies touches on rural areas, whether it is on agriculture, fisheries, natural environment or wildlife.</p><p> </p><p>There are currently 25 posts in Defra’s Rural Policy Team. All are involved in rural proofing, whether it is developing Defra’s approach, building the evidence base, engaging with stakeholders to identify concerns or working with other departments on specific issues.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, there are 29 posts in the team in Defra managing the Rural Development Programme for England.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-05-16T16:39:25.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125694/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125694/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-09","Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many civil servants are (a) fully and (b) partially employed in (i) rural policy development and (ii) checking rural proofing of other departments and public bodies.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","252508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125695","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-05-15","<p>Rural exception sites are used for affordable housing provided in perpetuity, on land that would not normally be released for development. While some market housing may be allowed on such sites, this is at the local planning authority’s discretion, and no threshold applies. On sites that are not exception sites, national policy is that affordable housing should be sought only on sites that involve major development, except in designated rural areas where a lower threshold may be set.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-05-15T09:45:43.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125695/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125695/answer","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125695/answer/previousversion/117984","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-05-09","Affordable Housing: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to reassess the threshold for affordable housing on rural exception sites.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","252509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125696","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-05-14","<p>The Department provides services to around 22 million people, and has a responsibility to communicate policy and essential information to claimants and other key audiences, in a similar way to other government departments. The ‘Opening Up Work’ campaign aims to increase understanding of how Universal Credit removes barriers to work and aids career progression, and to provide information to help people make a claim.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has spent the amounts shown in the table below with the Metro newspaper.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Spend (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>20,918.16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>23,628.96</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Source:</strong> DWP internal accounts</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2019-05-14T14:24:49.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125696/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125696/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-05-09","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much her Department has spent on advertising universal credit in the Metro newspaper to date; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","252567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125697","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-05-15","<p>A copy of a list showing land and buildings that are in the process of being disposed of has been placed in the Library of the House.</p><p>Some 47 sites on the report are empty, each site may contain multiple buildings.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2019-05-15T14:33:52.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125697/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125697/answer","252480 - List of MOD land and buildings being disposed.xlsx","252480 - List of MOD land and buildings being disposed.xlsx","List of MOD land and buildings being disposed","List of MOD land and buildings being disposed","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125697/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-05-09","Ministry of Defence: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if she will publish a list of (a) land and (b) buildings that her Department is in the process of selling and/or disposing of; how many of those buildings are empty; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","252480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125698","Home Office","false","2019-05-16","<p>No estimate has been made on this specific issue by the Home Office.</p><p>The scale and social &amp; economic costs associated with a number of Serious &amp; Organised Crimes including Drugs Supply and Human Trafficking are set out in the Understanding Organised Crime report (published November 2018).</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2019-05-16T10:40:06.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125698/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125698/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-05-09","Organised Crime: Proceeds of Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate he has made of the income that organised crime groups have made from criminal activity by (a) supplying and/or selling illegal drugs and (b) trafficking people in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","252481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125699","Department for Education","false","2019-05-14","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Amanda Spielman. I have asked her to write to the hon. Member and a copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-05-14T15:23:41.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125699/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125699/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-05-09","Schools: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many schools in England that are due to close have been inspected by Ofsted in the last 12 months; how much did each such inspection cost; and what the outcomes were of each of those inspections.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","252627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125700","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-16","<p>Sections 168 and 170 of the Equality Act 2010 already require drivers of taxis and PHVs to accept passengers accompanied by assistance dogs without charging them extra.</p><p> </p><p>The Government expects drivers to comply with the law and encourages local licensing authorities to take robust action against those unwilling to do so.</p><p> </p><p>Drivers convicted of a relevant offence face fines of up to £1000.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-05-16T10:04:40.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125700/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1125700/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-09","Taxis: Guide Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the potential merits of legislating to make it illegal for taxis and private hire vehicles to turn away guide dogs.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","252628"
